It is suggested that there is an expectations gap between what stakeholders expect and what boards of directors can reasonably contribute. This paper critiques this premise / assumption. It is posited that the lack of robust prior research findings is explained by this expectations gap. However, it is acknowledged that research design flaws also contribute to problems of prior research attempting to relate firm performance and corporate governance. \
