\i Differences in risk appetites of shareholders and directors
\i0 \
	> The amount of risk exposure, or potential adverse impact from an event that an org / individual is willing to accept / retain. Many shareholders have considerable risk appetites as they have the opportunity to diversify their risks by investing in a wide range of assets. \
	Managers are more risk averse, as their interests are tied to a single company (their employer). Directors are even more so. Not only are they tied to a single company, but the renumeration derived there from is relatively modest, while their most valuable asset (their reputation) is dependant on the company not being the subject of a scandal. Rather than contributing to shareholder value, their risk averse nature may have quite a contrary effect on contributing to shareholder value. \
